06340nam a22008535i 9780674736207DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013950673  a(OCoLC)979969935  a97806747362077 a10.4159/harvard.97806747362072doi  a(DE-B1597)427926  a(OCoLC)897599041  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aDS33.2b.A853 2015eb 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04a950/.322300aAsia Inside Out :bChanging Times /ced. by Eric Tagliacozzo. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (310 p.) :b21 halftones, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Structuring Moments in Asian Connections -- t1501 in Tabriz: From Tribal Takeover to Imperial Trading Circuit? Heidi A. Walcher -- t1555: Four Imperial Revivals -- t1557: A Year of Some Significance -- t1636 and 1726: Yemen after the First Ottoman Era -- t1683: An Off shore Perspective on Vietnamese Zen -- t1745: Ebbs and Flows in the Indian Ocean -- t1874: Tea and Japan’s New Trading Regime Robert Hellyer -- tChina and India Are One: A Subaltern’s Vision of “Hindu China” during the Boxer Expedition of 1900–1901 -- tBefore the Gangrene Set In: Th e Dutch East Indies in 1910 -- t1956: Bangalore’s Cosmpolitan Pasts and Monocultural Futures? -- t2008: “Open City” and a New Wave of Filipino Migration to the Middle East -- tContributors -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first of three volumes surveying the historical, spatial, and human dimensions of inter-Asian connections, Asia Inside Out: Changing Times brings into focus the diverse networks and dynamic developments that have linked peoples from Japan to Yemen over the past five centuries. Each author examines an unnoticed moment—a single year or decade—that redefined Asia in some important way. Heidi Walcher explores the founding of the Safavid dynasty in the crucial battle of 1501, while Peter C. Perdue investigates New World silver’s role in Sino-Portuguese and Sino-Mongolian relations after 1557. Victor Lieberman synthesizes imperial changes in Russia, Burma, Japan, and North India in the seventeenth century, Charles Wheeler focuses on Zen Buddhism in Vietnam to 1683, and Kerry Ward looks at trade in Pondicherry, India, in 1745. Nancy Um traces coffee exports from Yemen in 1636 and 1726, and Robert Hellyer follows tea exports from Japan to global markets in 1874. Anand Yang analyzes the diary of an Indian soldier who fought in China in 1900, and Eric Tagliacozzo portrays the fragility of Dutch colonialism in 1910. Andrew Willford delineates the erosion of cosmopolitan Bangalore in the mid-twentieth century, and Naomi Hosoda relates the problems faced by Filipino workers in Dubai in the twenty-first. Moving beyond traditional demarcations such as West, East, South, and Southeast Asia, this interdisciplinary study underscores the fluidity and contingency of trans-Asian social, cultural, economic, and political interactions. It also provides an analytically nuanced and empirically rich understanding of the legacies of Asian globalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh1 aHosoda, Naomi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLieberman, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerdue, Peter C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSiu, Helen F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTagliacozzo, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTagliacozzo, Eric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vo